SSPE
---
[9] Subacute sclerosing pan-encephalitis (SSPE)
Date: Tue 29 Oct 2019
Source: The Sun [abridged, edited]
https://www.thesun.co.uk/fabulous/10234521/boy-died-measles-dormant-virus/


A heartbroken mum whose 6 year old died from a dormant virus the measles left behind says she wishes she could "go back in time and bring him back." [The boy] died in April this year [2019] after a dormant virus left behind by measles he had as a baby flared up. [His mother has been left heartbroken after losing her son [when he] caught a wild strain of the measles before he could be vaccinated as a baby, developing the usual rash and high temperature associated with the illness.

He bounced back a week later and went on to be a funny, cheeky boy who loved dancing, Tom and Jerry, Arsenal FC and was top of his class at school. But just 6 years later he died of subacute [sclerosing] pan-encephalitis (SSPE), which is caused by dormant antibodies left behind by the measles virus which can attack healthy brain cells at any time.

His symptoms 1st appeared last December [2018], when a usually well-behaved child became naughty and argumentative. Then in February [2019], he told his mum he was "exhausted", became clumsy, forgetful, unable to dress himself properly and stopped doing his schoolwork. [His mum] took him straight to the GP, who advised she take him to A&E, where doctors couldn't pinpoint a reason for his bizarre mix of symptoms. His mum said: "They were asking him about school and said he couldn't keep up. It was like his brain was slowing down."

Around 18 in every 100 000 people who catch wild measles as babies will go on to develop SSPE; it is usually fatal and there is no cure.

[byline: Anna Donay]

--
communicated by:
ProMED-mail from HealthMap Alerts
<promed@promedmail.org>

[Subacute sclerosing panencephalitis (SSPE) is a rare condition that is caused by a measles infection acquired earlier in life. Signs and symptoms of the condition primarily affect the central nervous system and often develop approximately 7 to 10 years after a person recovers from the measles.

SSPE results from a long-term brain infection with the measles virus. The virus sometimes enters the brain during a measles infection. It may cause immediate symptoms of brain infection (encephalitis), or it may remain in the brain for a long time without causing problems.

SSPE occurs because the measles virus reactivates. In the past in the USA, for reasons that are not known, the disorder occurred in about 7 to 300 people per million people who had measles infection and in about one person per million people who received the measles vaccine. However, doctors think the people who developed SSPE after vaccination likely had a mild, undiagnosed case of measles before they were vaccinated and that the vaccine did not cause the SSPE (excerpted from https://www.merckmanuals.com/home/children-s-health-issues/viral-infections-in-infants-and-children/subacute-sclerosing-panencephalitis-sspe). - Mod.LK

